segments.text: Two things that I know Mr. Benson was working on that was very important.
He knew that the enrollment of Texas A&M, A&M's future, we either had to increase the enrollment or we had to decide what Texas A&M was going to be at that time because enrollment was not growing.
It was static.
And I'm not sure why, but
UT Arlington at that time was separated from Texas A&M.
That was a part of the A&M system, and why the decision was made to relinquish that and go to the UT system, I'm not sure, but I do remember working on some of those proposals.
I don't know who recommended it, and I remember a man by the name, seemed like his name was Dr. Wolf, that was the first president of UT Arlington, what became UT Arlington.
It had been Arlington State?
Yes, it had been Arlington State.
I don't know exactly what our presence was there and why we decided to give it up.
I don't know how those proposals came about.
I think that that was the board's plan is they would take all the A&M money and put it in one place.
And what they did was to narrow the political base that Texas A&M and the system could call upon.
And, of course, now there's exactly the opposite.
The opposite, right.
Yeah.
I can remember him writing letters on proposals

that we must work in the legislature to increase salaries for faculty that the salaries were so low that if A&M were to ever attract and today we still see that same statement being made we must stay competitive in salaries and he worked hard to try to do that and I would see some of the salary letters actually I typed a lot of the salary letters in engineering and I can remember I thought they were fairly good salaries at that time but
an engineer graduating, if he got a salary offer of seven or eight thousand dollars a year, that was a high salary going out with a bachelor's degree in engineering.
So if you saw a faculty person's salary that many of the faculty made no more than that, that seemed like a good salary, and of course it was a pathetic salary at that time.
Did y'all ever think about transferring or dropping out of college?
No, that was never an option.
No, we never considered that.
You were determined to... Oh yeah, we came to stay for Don to graduate.
And there weren't any crisis semesters in terms of his grades.

Yes, last semester, just before graduation, he had made a D in one of his petroleum engineering classes, and you had to take an additional test to make sure that you were going to graduate because you couldn't graduate with that D in your major, even in one course.
And I think he made a C in that course, and he graduated.
But it was a little tense that one semester.
As you...
you remember the routine.
As the years went on, did the hours of work and study for both of you
continue about the same?
Well, they were intense.

I can remember one year at Easter, we didn't even consider going home because Don had a major project that was due, and he spent the entire, we used to get Thursday and Friday before Easter off, and then the Saturday and Sunday, and he spent the entire four days, he and Jack Little and a few of the others spent at the petroleum engineering lab, and
Come to find out when they returned the next Monday, there were a few of them gave up on the problem and went home.
They found out from the professor it was unsolvable.
So we had stayed here the holiday to an unsolvable problem.
And he was testing them to see if they came up with a solution.
If we could interview some of the cross-section of his classmates, who do you think they would say were their favorite teachers, the ones they most appreciated?
I wish I could remember all the names in the Petroleum Engineering Department.
Many would name Mr. Whiting, Dr. Pettigo,
There were others.
I'd have to look at it.
If I could look at an annual, I can remember the names.
What about in some of the courses that were support outside petroleum engineering?
Were there some people in other courses that they?
Yeah, there was a history class that they all loved.
Remember who taught it?
I dealt with that without looking at the annual.
When we get the transcript back, if I can remember the names, I'll plug them in for you.
And were there some courses that they feared, that were tough?
Well, there probably were.
Like chemistry, math, physics?
Oh, I remember Don and Bob Lacy complaining more about calculus than they did anything.
They studied together and argued together around my kitchen table a lot.
But I think they knew that if anybody could pass them, if you worked hard enough, you could do it.
That was the worst thing.
Where did Lacy live in those days?
He lived in the dorm on campus without a car.
So the first two years, I don't think he had a car.
He might have had one the last two years.
But he spent a lot of time at our department.
And let's try to look at the student body from a different point of view.
Describe the typical.
person who lived at College View?
Were they Anglo?
Were they working class?
Were they from Texas?
The majority of students in the 56 to 60 were Texans that lived there.
Tuition was very low at Texas A&M.
There wasn't even a building use fee.
Rent was cheap in College View.
All the people that lived in College View were married.
The single people did live usually in the dorms on campus.
There wasn't much off-campus living for students.
The majority had very little money, so money was not an issue.
You didn't feel out of place, that we weren't trying to keep up with the Joneses, so to speak.
Some had fairly good running cars, and others had some that didn't run so well.
Some of us carpooled.
We took our own lunches.
There wasn't any place to eat on campus.
So you packed your lunch, or you went home for lunch.
What would have been a typical lunch for you that you packed?

um a bologna sandwich and chips and a piece of fruit don't remember taking a drink so there must have been a coke machine in the building but you know lots of bologna sandwiches when we were in school and of these students were they all small small town or big city or
Well, they were from both.
Houston, Dallas were most of the from that came from the city.
And then we came, of course, from near the Abilene area.
I don't remember a lot of students from far West Texas coming here.
I suspect they were going to Tech rather than coming here.
And I don't remember a lot from the Valley coming here.
So we were a little town.
You really wanted to come to Texas A&M to be here.
And on the weekends, did pretty well everybody stay here?
Oh, no, a lot of the Corps went home, and then there were weigh stations along the way for the Corps, particularly at Waco, and you could just stand in the weigh station, and they hitchhiked a lot.
But you knew if you were in your Corps uniform, somebody would pick you up.
Did you?
We always picked up students.
Did you?
If we were on Sunday coming home or if we were going home on Friday, we'd pick up students if they were going our direction.
Were they always well-behaved when you picked them up?
We never had a problem.
We didn't think about that.
I haven't run into anybody yet who remembers having a problem either as the one who picks them up or the one who was picked up.
No.
Two or three have said some guy tried to buy them a little more beer than they should have, or he drove too fast, but that's the worst thing they've ever mentioned.
Yeah, we never had any problem.
Let's see, on that, for you as a young woman, did any single Aggie ever attempt to flirt with you when you were in the office or anything?
Oh, yes.
Really?
Yes, you have that.
But you can handle it very much like you do today.
You let them know you're not interested, and they behaved.
They were well-behaved.
They knew your boss was right behind the door, and so they didn't really try a lot of things.
As far as y'all were aware,
if anybody had really wanted to go and venture a little, where did Aggies go to drink beer or anything else?
There was a place on Texas Avenue fairly close to where, what's the coffee shop over here on Texas Avenue right across from them?
The breakfast place.
Denny's?
Denny's.
There was a place there that some drank beer.
I can't remember the name of it.
There was a place called Martin's that they could drink beer.
And then some went to the river, so to speak.
To Whiskey Bridge?
To Whiskey Bridge, so to speak, yes, to drink.
Did married students ever go to the clay pits to swim?
I don't know what the clay pits were.

There was a place out here, and it was an old, where they had scooped clay out of the ground, and there was water in there, stagnant water, and that's where students would sometimes go to swim and drink a little bit of beer.
I wasn't even aware it was there.
But we came here as married students, so we were never in that single life of...
Did you all ever have beer at your apartment?
Yes, for special occasions.
Sometimes the whole apartment complex would have a Friday night cookout, cook hamburgers.
We might have a little beer.
I'm not sure that we could have beer outside the apartments.
In student housing, you could have it inside.
And all of the area, the green space where College View is now,
At that time, that was full of apartments, is that right?
That's correct, yes.
It was just row after row of apartments.
Was the coin-operated wash-a-terrier up near where the Ramada would be built?
Was it yet there?
That one wasn't there, but there was a coin-operated one near Erleberg Shopping Center because I do remember taking laundry on Saturday
Once I got a washing machine, I'd take it up there to dry it.
So I know there was a coin-operated one on Texas Avenue near the Early Bird Shopping Center.
As far as you can recall, about what percentage of the people that you knew in College View had a washing machine?
Oh, maybe 50.
And no one had a dryer because they weren't wired for a dryer.
You didn't even have.
So it wouldn't matter if you could afford.
Yeah.
And about how many had a TV?
Oh, probably 50%.
And telephone?
Fifty to sixty percent, yeah.
Did you all stay in the same apartment?
Yes.
Three and a half years.
Three and a half years.
Now in the summers, what was the routine for you all?
summer classes.
Don was in class by seven.
He always took at least six hours each term.
We had two long terms and work and study and maybe a driving movie and that was it.
Did y'all keep the paper route a long time?
Probably a couple of years.
And you stayed in the dean's office all that time?
Except for the one year that I worked in the placement office.
Yeah, yeah.
I worked in the placement office from September 56 to November 57, and then in the dean's office until Don graduated in May of 60.
Let's see, and you never thought about dropping out, never thought about transferring.
No grade, no grade crises.
Except one course.
Yeah, yeah.
And there was, I'm not sure there was, I'm not sure you could drop a course and have a cue drop as you do today.
So that was never an option.
You didn't think about cue dropping a course.
Right.
Can you remember your husband going to seek the advice of somebody, some faculty member, and in hindsight the advice that he got was important?
or somebody gave him guidance, counsel, that turned out to be him?
Well, yes.
He was a student member of Tau Beta Pi, the Engineering Honor Society.
And one of his best friends was running for president of the Engineering Honor Society.
His name was Michael McGuire.
And he was the, matter of fact, he was the, had the highest grade point ratio on campus of any student.
And so Don was working in his campaign.

Someone suggested that Don run, and of course he didn't consider doing that at all, because he was going to work for Mike, and then he was nominated from the floor the night of the election and was elected president of Taubatuckapai.
I didn't really want to go to work the next morning because I was working for Mr. McGuire, the father of Mike McGuire at that time, and I knew that was not going to be a real happy day for him.

But it turned out that Don's faculty person had told him, you know, this would be a good thing for him to do because he'd go to national meetings and be exposed to some things that he wouldn't be exposed to on campus.
And sure enough, he got to go to the national convention, which was held at...
trying to remember where it was held.
Anyway, I do remember that he had to have at least two suits to go, and he didn't have those.
And so we had to figure out how to save enough money for him to get two suits to go to the National Convention.
It was at Purdue.
That's where it was held, yeah.
So that turned out to be good advice for him and made him a lot more so, gave him a lot more confidence in what he could do.
All right, now you're mentioning the two suits.
What would have been his and your wardrobe at that?
How many outfits?
Well, I can remember very carefully, I can remember when I was pregnant how many I had.
I had exactly, the first time I was pregnant, I think I had four.
And so you worked five days a week, so you had to figure out how to get it washed and dried and ironed so you could,
have another time.
And then in 1960, when I was pregnant, I think I actually had five outfits that I could wear.
And even when I wasn't pregnant, there was very limited wardrobe.
I had come with a few clothes.
How many winter coats, long coats?
Oh, you only had one.
You didn't even consider having more than that.
And a pair of shoes.
Well, I probably had two.
I had a very hard foot to fit, and I had to order my shoes, and they were very expensive, so I might have had two.
And did a woman working in the office wear high heels?
Oh, yes, yes.
We were expected to wear high heels, yes.
And sweaters?
Yeah, we could wear sweaters.
But they were just like a cordigan sweater that we would wear.
Do you remember any woman ever attempting to push the dress code during that era?
No, not really.
Because don't I remember, weren't you the one under Calhoun that went on behalf of the group to ask if it would be all right to wear
dress slacks, pantsuits, I want to say.
Because I thought it would.
This is in the 70s.
This is in the 70s.
Yes, I think I did ask Calhoun if we could wear a pantsuit because pantsuits had come in into the 70s as an outfit.
And wasn't his response to kind of chuckle?
Yeah, he did.
And say, of course?
Of course, he did.
But we didn't have any pantsuits during the 50s.
It was dresses.
Were there any scandals during the 50s that you heard of on campus of a secretary and some important person?
We're not going to name any names.
Were there any scandals of somebody courting somebody else's secretary, anything like that?
I've not heard of any.
If there were, I wasn't aware of them.
Because I remember one time hearing Dean Benson say that he thought the unwritten rules at that point were you never serve alcohol at an event where there are students.
That's correct.
If you are divorcing or heading toward a divorce and you get another job at another institution, and if you're gambling, playing poker or anything like that for money,
You closed the blinds and the curtains.
I remember there were a few faculty members that had a drinking problem during the 50s.
And they were brought in for counseling by Mr. Benson or Mr. Crawford.
But other than that, those were probably the only scandals.
What about faculty members meeting class?
How often did they fail to meet class?
I wasn't aware that they never not showed.
And how many hours a day were they available for students?
Oh, they were there all day.
Any time a student wanted to see their faculty member, they could go by, and they would be there unless they were in class teaching another section.
So finding your prof was not a problem during the 50s.
And how did faculty members dress in that era?
usually just pants and shirt, tie, and many times they very few wore coats, and there certainly were no sandals, and there were no shorts.
What about their haircut and their facial hair?
They could have some facial hair, but they usually had short hair.
There was no long hair.
Did they have beards?
I'm not sure.
Some of them may have had some beard, but it was well-trimmed.
There were no long beards, no long hair, no ponytails, no blue jeans.
During the 50s, were there any student, far-out activities here?
Well, when you say far out, there were some things like the Corps would allow women to come into the dorms, and that was against the rules.
And then they would do crazy things like put them in the laundry bags to get them out of the dorms so that no one would know they were there.
So yes, we heard about some of those and some of the names of some of the dorms and some of the names of the women that were brought in for that.
Those were crazy activities that took place, and then occasionally students would go during deer season and shoot deer and then gut it and clean it in the shower stalls within the dorms.
But those students were single students usually that were living in the dorms, very few married students in the dorms.
Did your husband do any hunting or fishing while you all were here?
No.
We camped out a couple of times.
near Huntsville, just a tent to cook out overnight and just to sleep out on cots and things like that.
But we were not big hunters or fishermen.
How often did you all go to Houston or Dallas or Austin?
We never went to Austin.
And we went to Houston to the Fat Stock Show.
And Dallas, we went maybe...
once or twice a year with the Smithwicks because his family lived there on Campbell Road in Richardson.
Richard Dick Smithwick was one of them.
Well, he was the first Bear Bryant recruit out of Richardson, Texas.
And we'd go there to stay with his family a couple of times a year.
A while ago, I meant to ask, were there any Hispanic students living anywhere near you all?
Did you know any Hispanic?
Well, I don't know that they were Hispanic.
We didn't think about it as Hispanic.
There were some from Puerto Rico.
Okay.
But they probably came here through way of Louisiana.
And how were they received?
Well received.
They were good friends.
I mean, we didn't think about them any differently.
As far as I remember, though, there were no African-American students here at that time.
I cannot remember any African-American students.
Were there any Jewish students?
Oh, yeah, there were Jewish students here.
And how were they?
Well, we just saw them as the same classmate, you know, as an equal classmate.
There was not a lot of discrimination, I don't think, here in the 50s, early 60s.
People were here for an education.
It was a serious business.
And thinking about your future career, I think that was the main goals of students.
We were not concerned a lot about student life.
That was not a big issue on campus.
To fit you in with the culture was not the university's goal.
It was academics and studies.
Would you all walk from College View over to the MSC sometimes after?
No, we usually drove.
Oh, did you?
Yeah, we had a car most of the time, and we would normally drive.
Would you sometimes get at the snack bar?
No, not a lot.
We didn't have a lot of discretionary funds, so we didn't do that.
the, let's see, we talked about the churches and so forth, and I was trying to think about other diversity issues.
Women were
were politely treated by the students.
Oh, every student spoke to you, yes.
Howdy was a typical response.
They spoke first and expected you to speak back.
Now, there was no effort, no campaign to orient you student wives about Aggie traditions.
If there was, it was through your own departmental club, if you did.
So after you, say, joined petroleum engineering wives, they may have talked about traditions, but no, I don't remember any orientation for me.
And then when your husband graduated, the wife got a little diploma that said putting hubby through.
Most of us put it up in our laundry rooms.
Was there a Breckenridge hometown club?
No, not that I remember.
There might have been, but I wasn't really involved in it at all.
When did you begin to feel that you were part of the Aggie group, the Aggie family?
How long did that take?
I think we were much, felt much more a part of the Aggie family after we left than when we were here.
Oh, really?
Uh-huh.
Because we were so busy while we were here, you didn't think about those things.
And then as A&M began to grow and its reputation began to increase, I think we were proud to have been Aggies, I guess.
So the pride was more after than while here?
Uh-huh.
For us, it was.
We didn't have anyone that, you know, our ties were not as strong.
But we realized our future was built on what we had accomplished here, yes.
Don's degree served him well.
Right.
And there was no, he didn't do a summer working somewhere
out for a company?
No, he had already done that so that he got academic credit for that internship because he had done prior work and certified that.
Okay, and what was the activity then?
How were young men prepared for their interviews and that first job?
I don't think there was a lot of preparation.

I think you came by the placement office, got your credentials ready, signed up for your interviews and showed up for your interviews, but there was not an orientation as to how to conduct yourself in that interview.
And do you remember where the interviews were held?
Oh, they were held at the placement office.
Which was, okay, where then?
the little building that was torn down, the frame building that was torn down.
There might have been a few in the MSC if they ran out of space.
And I remember that a lot of the companies came and always seemed very polite to us.
The interviewers came.
What, for you all in the dean's office,
What feedback did you all get from the interviewers about their impression of the Aggies?
Most of the impressions that I got came from the placement office rather than the dean's office.
The feedback came to Mr. Horsley and to Mr. Hensel.
And they felt that they had the cream of the crop, so to speak.
Teachers were hired, those that went into teaching as a profession, math majors taught a lot.
So, yeah, school districts came, engineering companies came, chemical companies came.
It was a big season always in the fall when the interviewers came.
We had a few come in the spring, but most interviewing was done in the fall.
Oh, really?
Mm-hmm.
Even for... May graduates.
For a job, for May graduates, okay.
Alright, in your case, when did the interviewing begin for your husband?
Senior year.
Senior year.
Do you remember how many companies he interviewed with?
I don't remember how many he interviewed with.
I remember he got five offers.
I do remember that.
And do you remember what the offer was that he took?
How much money?
He went to work for ARCO, and I think it was about $7,000 a year, and we thought that was big money.
Was it already called ARCO, or was it Atlantic Refining?
It was Atlantic Refining at that time, yes.
And he was to report when, where?
Well, right after graduation, we were to report to...
Longview, Texas.
He was actually there at a plant called near Gladewater.
And so we lived in Longview.
And I remember that we went out to house hunt.
We didn't know we could ask for an advance on our salary.
So we had a little money that we were going to look for a place, look for a place to live and rent an apartment.
And we had to stay a couple of days longer than we anticipated.
We ran out of money and we counted our bank money.
We sat on the floor and rolled the pennies and dimes to pay for the advance during that time.
And you still didn't have furniture.
Oh, no, we didn't have any furniture.
We had a baby bed and a chest and a bookcase and an air conditioner.
I think I had one in a raffle or something.
And that same car.
And the same car, correct.
Okay.
Let's see.
No final review for this veteran.
Commencement was held where?
Do you remember?
In Gone Hall.
Do you remember?
Was there an important speaker?
Do you remember?
I don't remember who it was.
It was on a Saturday morning, I do remember that.
And who, what family, what loved ones came?
Don's mother came from New York for the graduation.
And Don's brother, who had cancer, and he had been staying with us a lot because he had been in Houston taking treatments all of Don's senior year.
And he and his wife and their little boy and my sister and her two children came for that event.
And there was an apartment next to us that was going to be empty, and we borrowed that one so that we had our apartment and the empty one for the company.
So that's how we arranged it.
And what were your feelings when this special person started to walk across the stage?
Oh, I was elated.
It had been a long four years.
Was there anything, did anybody do anything humorous at that commencement?
Oh no, it was a serious ceremony.
Everybody was serious?
And they did get their diploma?
In the tube at that time, that's correct.
